tweet: @shrimpoi @milesjennings @a16z 🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻 thank you!

name: Laura Shin
tweet: @jswihart @milesjennings @a16z No, my guess would be creators would only exercise that right if you use it in some way that is reasonably objectionable. Like if you used it to incite violence. I doubt they would abuse it — it would make the value of the collection go down.

name: Laura Shin
tweet: Most NFT licenses aren’t on-chain, which means there’s a question of whether they're even enforceable. @milesjennings explains how @a16z’s “can’t be evil” NFT licenses address this and other problems in the NFT space: https://t.co/AVUp9pAz47 https://t.co/OMBhiTIsif

name: Laura Shin
tweet: @ChrisBlec Since some people react negatively to them, some creators may opt not to go with a license with that right, as a competitive advantage.

name: Laura Shin
tweet: @ChrisBlec This is optional. Some licenses have this and some don’t. It’s up to the creator. If you don’t like that, you don’t have to buy one of the ones with that in the license.

name: Laura Shin
tweet: @Paul__Walsh I think the point isn’t that a16z thinks they’re creating something so novel as just a quick and easy way to creators to specify what rights go with their NFT rather than having to explain it all. Like when someone says, “CC0,” people know what that is. Same idea here.

name: Laura Shin
tweet: @0xrebal @milesjennings @a16z Oh good idea. I was thinking more from the creator perspective. Like, some models say they wouldn’t do ads for tobacco or alcohol companies. This is similar to that — saying, I don’t want my creation used to promote certain things.

name: Laura Shin
tweet: @JStein_WaPo I wouldn’t jump to just lumping all pro-crypto stances in traditional buckets like libertarian. It’s a movement that really draws all sorts of strange bedfellows and is not easily classifiable, because it creates totally new paradigms. Decentralization really changes everything

name: Laura Shin
tweet: @JStein_WaPo Both Wyden and Warner are consistent in that these networks and developers present a threat to traditional business, so Warner’s amendment kills a potential competitor while Wyden’s allows it to keep developing here in the US

name: Laura Shin
tweet: @JStein_WaPo It actually makes sense because the “crypto industry” as you call it is trying to protect decentralized networks and protocol developers, which it’s not logical/possible to put under this tax regime, while agreeing that it makes sense to tax the traditional crypto businesses

name: Laura Shin
tweet: @JStein_WaPo In short, money will move faster, more globally across borders (except maybe China the way the internet is bifurcated now), and in a way that is more empowering to everyday people rather than to big institutions

name: Laura Shin
tweet: @JStein_WaPo There’s so much innovation happening now, these tweets only scratch the surface. There is so much more coming and so much we can’t even see yet. There are downsides to many of the things I’ve mentioned, like increased hacks, but people are working on ways to mitigate already

name: Laura Shin
tweet: @JStein_WaPo In general, you’ll be able to do a lot more things with your money since it will be programmable. People are already giving themselves loans using money they already have as collateral, without having to deal with the blind spots of FICO scores

name: Laura Shin
tweet: @JStein_WaPo If you’re a creator, you’ll have more ways to monetize your work and have a direct financial relationship to your audience rather than using legacy systems in which middlemen take cuts from what your fans pay before the money reaches you

name: Laura Shin
tweet: @JStein_WaPo You’ll have more ways to keep your money secure from things like a run on the bank, such as seen in certain economies, or from governmental policies that deflate your money, and if you’re in a situation where you have to flee, you’ll be able to take your savings with you

name: Laura Shin
tweet: @JStein_WaPo You’ll be able to automate more of your finances without paying fees to banks. You’ll pay fees to the network, but since you’ll also own the network’s tokens, as long as the economics of the system are set up correctly, you’ll benefit financially from usage of the network

name: Laura Shin
tweet: @JStein_WaPo Some will be votes in DAOs (decentralized autonomous organizations), which will replace big companies as the way we provide internet products and services. In a DAO, you’ll be a user-owner, voting on how the DAO is run, plus benefit financially from being an owner through tokens

name: Laura Shin
tweet: @JStein_WaPo The way that you now wake up and check your messages on multiple platforms, in the future, you’ll wake up and have various financial transactions that happened overnight, some with people you’ll never meet in real life, from communities that are now under- and un-banked.

2) I really don’t regret it. If I did, I could have easily bought some again and just disclosed like I used to do. As I mentioned, I work for myself. One of my mottos is to live life with no regrets, and I’d say my track record is excellent on this score.

One more thing:

name: Laura Shin
tweet: To the people tweeting at me “have fun staying poor,” and that I actually do regret not owning Bitcoin for now, I’d like to say: 1) I’m having the time of my life. And I consider myself rich in many, many, many things that other people do not have — just not BTC, for now

name: Laura Shin
tweet: As I said before, Michael gave a great answer here and I’m glad so many of you enjoyed it. But at least some of you are mistaken in thinking that my own personal views were in line with the premise of the question. FIN

name: Laura Shin
tweet: Personally, I love it when I ask a question and the guest pushes back at me. It makes for a more engaging interview. My past interviews with CZ are a great example of this.

name: Laura Shin
tweet: To sum up: In interviews I often ask questions that don’t reflect my personal beliefs. I do remember at least once pointing out that I was completely switching sides and now asking my guest to ask questions from the exact opposite viewpoint of my previous questions.

name: Laura Shin
tweet: It’s a fact that that has happened over and over again in Bitcoin’s history. I love that Michael said that just because it happened repeatedly in the past doesn’t mean it will happen again.

name: Laura Shin
tweet: And for those of taking issue with the fact that I said there could be another cycle with huge drawdowns, Willy Woo said exactly the same thing in my Real Vision interview with him on Friday. So are you going to attack him now?

name: Laura Shin
tweet: My personal belief did not matter and if I had inserted my opinion and not asked it because I think he shouldn’t do that, then we wouldn’t have had this great answer.

name: Laura Shin
tweet: Another basic rule of personal finance: If an investment makes sense for your portfolio, then it makes sense and what the market is doing or not doing should not affect that judgment.

name: Laura Shin
tweet: I covered personal finance for years. One of the rules of personal finance is not to try to time your buys and sells. I’m sure I have written about why this is a bad idea. (You have to get two things right and most people get at least one wrong if not both.)

name: Laura Shin
tweet:
Last note on this. I still see people saying that I was “wrong” or that I was biased. 

Let me repeat, a little more directly now: This question did not reflect my personal opinion.

name: Laura Shin
tweet: @BrendanEich @nope78547666 @StanfordMed @WSJ I don’t see how you got that from anything I said. Given that, at least in NY, the virus currently has a doubling rate of 3 days (reflective of activity a couple weeks ago), and given that we don’t have anywhere near the number of tests we need, the only option is to distance

name: Laura Shin
tweet: @nope78547666 @BrendanEich @StanfordMed @WSJ The economy isn’t going to pick up unless we resolve the coronavirus issue. Also, there’s a huge economic cost to letting a bunch of people get sick or die. If we do what we need to do now to prevent those things (plus get a lot more testing in place), then we can leave our homes

name: Laura Shin
tweet: @BrendanEich @StanfordMed @WSJ Another way to put it is that the only way we get to the low fatality rate is by taking measures that look too extreme. (Since we were too late on testing.) When we let up on distancing because we “believe” in this low fatality rate, then the fatality rate will shoot up.

name: Laura Shin
tweet: @BrendanEich @StanfordMed @WSJ There isn’t an abstract fatality rate — it will vary region by region and be determined by whether the local health care system got overwhelmed.

name: Laura Shin
tweet: @BrendanEich @StanfordMed @WSJ But our behaviors determine the fatality rate. Since this is so infectious and patients take weeks to recover, and since we didn’t test early and get ahead of it, the only thing left for us to do, to keep our fatality rate from being high, is to stay away from each other.

name: Laura Shin
